eed to find all E2E test function names in the e2e/tests/ directory and understand the test progression/tiers. Search for all `func Test` declarations in e2e/tests/ and also check e2e/README.md for any tier documentation. Return the full list of test function names and any tier/ordering information.\",\"agentId\":\"aa307aecb480efc9b\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01QtpEfJnyAV6sznan3xQTiZ\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01W7Ez4ig9AR7DQDJGuyjBjC\",\"uuid\":\"1cce2426-ada5-4787-8e47-c1ab75e151a5\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:32:27.602Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1cce2426-ada5-4787-8e47-c1ab75e151a5\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"b6cafcb4-19c4-45c6-9e59-cc361ef5d6b9\",\"version\":\"2.1.61\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"snuggly-beaming-peacock\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01QTeZMsRHV9Do5SRf7BMmFT\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Checkpoint Scenarios\\n     2→\\n     3→This document describes how the one-to-one checkpoint system handles various user workflows.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Overview\\n     6→\\n     7→The system uses:\\n     8→- **Shadow branches** (`entire/<commit-hash>-<worktree-hash>`) - temporary storage for checkpoint data\\n     9→- **FilesTouched** - accumulates files modified during the session\\n    10→- **1:1 checkpoints** - each commit gets its own unique checkpoint ID\\n    11→- **Content-aware overlap** - prevents linking commits where user reverted session changes\\n    12→\\n    13→## State Machine\\n    14→\\n    15→```mermaid\\n    16→stateDiagram-v2\\n    17→    [*] --> IDLE : SessionStart\\n    18→\\n    19→    IDLE --> ACTIVE : TurnStart (UserPromptSubmit)\\n    20→    ACTIVE --> IDLE : TurnEnd (Stop hook)\\n    21→    ACTIVE --> ACTIVE : GitCommit / Condense\\n    22→    IDLE --> IDLE : GitCommit / Condense\\n    23→\\n    24→    IDLE --> ENDED : SessionStop\\n    25→    ACTIVE --> ENDED : SessionStop\\n    26→    ENDED --> ACTIVE : TurnStart (session resume)\\n    27→    ENDED --> ENDED : GitCommit / CondenseIfFilesTouched\\n    28→```\\n    29→\\n    30→---\\n    31→\\n    32→## Scenario 1: Prompt → Changes → Prompt Finishes → User Commits\\n    33→\\n    34→The simplest workflow: user runs a prompt, Claude makes changes, prompt finishes, then user manually commits.\\n    35→\\n    36→```mermaid\\n    37→sequenceDiagram\\n    38→    participant U as User\\n    39→    participant C as Claude\\n    40→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n    41→    participant S as Session State\\n    42→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n    43→\\n    44→    U->>C: Submit prompt\\n    45→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit hook\\n    46→    G->>S: InitializeSession (IDLE→ACTIVE)\\n    47→    S->>S: TurnID generated\\n    48→\\n    49→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C)\\n    50→    C->>G: SaveChanges (Stop hook)\\n    51→    G->>SB: Write checkpoint (A, B, C + transcript)\\n    52→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C]\\n    53→    Note over G: TurnEnd: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n    54→\\n    55→    Note over U: Later...\\n    56→    U->>G: git commit -a\\n    57→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg hook\\n    58→    G->>S: Check FilesTouched [A, B, C]\\n    59→    G->>G: staged [A,B,C] ∩ FilesTouched → overlap ✓\\n    60→    G->>G: Generate checkpoint ID, add trailer\\n    61→\\n    62→    Note over G: PostCommit hook\\n    63→    G->>G: EventGitCommit (IDLE)\\n    64→    G->>SB: Condense to entire/checkpoints/v1\\n    65→    G->>SB: Delete shadow branch\\n    66→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n    67→```\\n    68→\\n    69→### Key Points\\n    70→- Shadow branch holds checkpoint data until user commits\\n    71→- PrepareCommitMsg adds `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer\\n    72→- PostCommit condenses to permanent storage and cleans up\\n    73→\\n    74→---\\n    75→\\n    76→## Scenario 2: Prompt Commits Within Single Turn\\n    77→\\n    78→Claude is instructed to commit changes, so the commit happens during the ACTIVE phase.\\n    79→\\n    80→```mermaid\\n    81→sequenceDiagram\\n    82→    participant U as User\\n    83→    participant C as Claude\\n    84→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n    85→    participant S as Session State\\n    86→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n    87→\\n    88→    U->>C: \\\"Make changes and commit them\\\"\\n    89→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit hook\\n    90→    G->>S: InitializeSession (→ACTIVE)\\n    91→\\n    92→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B)\\n    93→    C->>G: git add && git commit\\n    94→\\n    95→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg (no TTY = agent commit)\\n    96→    G->>G: Generate checkpoint ID, add trailer directly\\n    97→\\n    98→    Note over G: PostCommit hook (ACTIVE)\\n    99→    G->>G: EventGitCommit (ACTIVE→ACTIVE)\\n   100→    G->>SB: Condense with provisional transcript\\n   101→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs += [checkpoint-id]\\n   102→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   103→\\n   104→    C->>G: Responds with summary\\n   105→    Note over G: Stop hook\\n   106→    G->>G: HandleTurnEnd (ACTIVE→IDLE)\\n   107→    G->>G: UpdateCommitted: finalize with full transcript\\n   108→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\\n   109→```\\n   110→\\n   111→### Key Points\\n   112→- Agent commits detected by no TTY → fast path adds trailer directly\\n   113→- **Deferred finalization**: PostCommit saves provisional transcript, HandleTurnEnd updates with full transcript\\n   114→- TurnCheckpointIDs tracks mid-turn checkpoints for finalization at stop\\n   115→\\n   116→---\\n   117→\\n   118→## Scenario 3: Claude Makes Multiple Granular Commits\\n   119→\\n   120→Claude is instructed to make granular commits, resulting in multiple commits during one turn.\\n   121→\\n   122→```mermaid\\n   123→sequenceDiagram\\n   124→    participant U as User\\n   125→    participant C as Claude\\n   126→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   127→    participant S as Session State\\n   128→\\n   129→    U->>C: \\\"Implement feature with granular commits\\\"\\n   130→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   131→\\n   132→    C->>C: Creates file A\\n   133→    C->>G: git commit -m \\\"Add A\\\"\\n   134→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-1\\n   135→    Note over G: PostCommit (ACTIVE)\\n   136→    G->>G: Condense checkpoint-1 (provisional)\\n   137→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = [checkpoint-1]\\n   138→\\n   139→    C->>C: Creates file B\\n   140→    C->>G: git commit -m \\\"Add B\\\"\\n   141→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-2\\n   142→    Note over G: PostCommit (ACTIVE)\\n   143→    G->>G: Condense checkpoint-2 (provisional)\\n   144→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = [checkpoint-1, checkpoint-2]\\n   145→\\n   146→    C->>C: Creates file C\\n   147→    C->>G: git commit -m \\\"Add C\\\"\\n   148→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-3\\n   149→    Note over G: PostCommit (ACTIVE)\\n   150→    G->>G: Condense checkpoint-3 (provisional)\\n   151→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = [checkpoint-1, checkpoint-2, checkpoint-3]\\n   152→\\n   153→    C->>G: Summary response\\n   154→    Note over G: Stop hook → HandleTurnEnd\\n   155→    G->>G: Finalize ALL checkpoints with full transcript\\n   156→    Note right of G: checkpoint-1: UpdateCommitted<br/>checkpoint-2: UpdateCommitted<br/>checkpoint-3: UpdateCommitted\\n   157→    G->>S: TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\\n   158→```\\n   159→\\n   160→### Key Points\\n   161→- Each commit gets its own unique checkpoint ID (1:1 model)\\n   162→- All checkpoints are finalized together at turn end\\n   163→- Each checkpoint has the full session transcript for context\\n   164→\\n   165→---\\n   166→\\n   167→## Scenario 4: User Splits Changes Into Multiple Commits\\n   168→\\n   169→User decides to create multiple commits from Claude's changes after the prompt finishes.\\n   170→\\n   171→```mermaid\\n   172→sequenceDiagram\\n   173→    participant U as User\\n   174→    participant C as Claude\\n   175→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   176→    participant S as Session State\\n   177→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   178→\\n   179→    U->>C: Submit prompt\\n   180→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   181→\\n   182→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C, D)\\n   183→    C->>G: SaveChanges (Stop hook)\\n   184→    G->>SB: Write checkpoint (A, B, C, D)\\n   185→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C, D]\\n   186→    Note over G: TurnEnd: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   187→\\n   188→    Note over U: User commits A, B only\\n   189→    U->>G: git add A B && git commit\\n   190→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-1\\n   191→    Note over G: PostCommit (IDLE)\\n   192→    G->>G: committedFiles = {A, B}\\n   193→    G->>G: remaining = [C, D]\\n   194→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   195→    G->>SB: Carry-forward C, D to new shadow branch\\n   196→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [C, D]\\n   197→\\n   198→    Note over U: User commits C, D\\n   199→    U->>G: git add C D && git commit\\n   200→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-2\\n   201→    Note over G: PostCommit (IDLE)\\n   202→    G->>G: committedFiles = {C, D}\\n   203→    G->>G: remaining = []\\n   204→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   205→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   206→```\\n   207→\\n   208→### Key Points\\n   209→- **Carry-forward logic**: uncommitted files get a new shadow branch\\n   210→- Each commit gets its own checkpoint ID (1:1 model)\\n   211→- Both checkpoints link to the same session transcript\\n   212→\\n   213→### Content-Aware Carry-Forward\\n   214→\\n   215→The carry-forward logic uses **content-aware comparison** to determine which files have remaining uncommitted changes:\\n   216→\\n   217→1. **File not in commit** → definitely has remaining changes\\n   218→2. **File in commit, hash matches shadow branch** → fully committed, no carry-forward\\n   219→3. **File in commit, hash differs from shadow branch** → partial commit (e.g., `git add -p`), carry forward\\n   220→\\n   221→This enables splitting changes within a single file across multiple commits (see Scenario 7).\\n   222→\\n   223→---\\n   224→\\n   225→## Scenario 5: Partial Commit → Stash → Next Prompt\\n   226→\\n   227→User commits some changes, stashes the rest, then runs another prompt.\\n   228→\\n   229→```mermaid\\n   230→sequenceDiagram\\n   231→    participant U as User\\n   232→    participant C as Claude\\n   233→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   234→    participant S as Session State\\n   235→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   236→\\n   237→    U->>C: Prompt 1\\n   238→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   239→\\n   240→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C)\\n   241→    C->>G: Stop hook\\n   242→    G->>SB: Checkpoint (A, B, C)\\n   243→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C]\\n   244→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   245→\\n   246→    Note over U: User commits A only\\n   247→    U->>G: git add A && git commit\\n   248→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   249→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   250→    G->>SB: Carry-forward B, C\\n   251→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [B, C]\\n   252→\\n   253→    Note over U: User stashes B, C\\n   254→    U->>U: git stash\\n   255→    Note right of U: B, C removed from working directory<br/>FilesTouched still = [B, C]\\n   256→\\n   257→    U->>C: Prompt 2\\n   258→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit (IDLE→ACTIVE)\\n   259→    G->>S: TurnID = new, TurnCheckpointIDs = nil\\n   260→    Note right of G: FilesTouched NOT cleared<br/>(accumulates across prompts)\\n   261→\\n   262→    C->>C: Makes changes (D, E)\\n   263→    C->>G: SaveChanges\\n   264→    G->>SB: Add D, E to shadow branch tree\\n   265→    Note right of SB: Tree now has: B, C (old) + D, E (new)\\n   266→    G->>S: FilesTouched = merge([B,C], [D,E]) = [B,C,D,E]\\n   267→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   268→\\n   269→    Note over U: User commits D, E\\n   270→    U->>G: git add D E && git commit\\n   271→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg\\n   272→    G->>G: staged [D,E] ∩ FilesTouched [B,C,D,E] → D,E match ✓\\n   273→    G->>G: checkpoint-2 trailer added\\n   274→\\n   275→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   276→    G->>G: committedFiles = {D, E}\\n   277→    G->>G: remaining = [B, C]\\n   278→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   279→    Note right of G: Checkpoint has FULL session transcript<br/>(both Prompt 1 and Prompt 2)\\n   280→\\n   281→    G->>G: Carry-forward attempt for B, C\\n   282→    Note right of G: B, C don't exist on disk (stashed)<br/>→ removed from tree\\n   283→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [B, C]\\n   284→```\\n   285→\\n   286→### Key Points\\n   287→- **FilesTouched accumulates** across prompts (not cleared at TurnStart)\\n   288→- **Checkpoints have full session context**: D, E commit links to transcript showing BOTH prompts\\n   289→- **No wrong attribution**: Looking at checkpoint-2, you can see D, E were created by Prompt 2\\n   290→\\n   291→### Edge Case: Stashed Files Lose Shadow Content\\n   292→\\n   293→After user commits D, E, the carry-forward for B, C creates an \\\"empty\\\" checkpoint:\\n   294→- `buildTreeWithChanges` removes non-existent files (B, C are stashed) from the tree\\n   295→- A shadow branch commit is created, but its tree is just HEAD (no B, C content)\\n   296→- `FilesTouched` is set to `[B, C]` - the files are still **tracked by name**\\n   297→\\n   298→**If user later unstashes B, C and commits them:**\\n   299→- PrepareCommitMsg: staged [B, C] overlaps with FilesTouched [B, C] by filename → trailer added ✓\\n   300→- PostCommit: checkpoint is created and linked\\n   301→- But the shadow branch doesn't have the original B, C content from Prompt 1\\n   302→\\n   303→This is acceptable behavior - stashing files mid-session and committing other files first is an explicit user action. The files are still tracked, but the shadow branch content chain is broken.\\n   304→\\n   305→---\\n   306→\\n   307→## Scenario 6: Stash → Second Prompt → Unstash → Commit All\\n   308→\\n   309→User stashes files, runs another prompt, then unstashes and commits everything together.\\n   310→\\n   311→```mermaid\\n   312→sequenceDiagram\\n   313→    participant U as User\\n   314→    participant C as Claude\\n   315→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   316→    participant S as Session State\\n   317→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   318→\\n   319→    U->>C: Prompt 1\\n   320→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   321→\\n   322→    C->>C: Makes changes (A, B, C)\\n   323→    C->>G: Stop hook\\n   324→    G->>SB: Checkpoint (A, B, C)\\n   325→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A, B, C]\\n   326→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   327→\\n   328→    Note over U: User commits A only\\n   329→    U->>G: git add A && git commit\\n   330→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   331→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   332→    G->>SB: Carry-forward B, C\\n   333→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [B, C]\\n   334→\\n   335→    Note over U: User stashes B, C\\n   336→    U->>U: git stash\\n   337→    Note right of U: B, C removed from working directory<br/>Shadow branch still has B, C\\n   338→\\n   339→    U->>C: Prompt 2\\n   340→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit (IDLE→ACTIVE)\\n   341→\\n   342→    C->>C: Makes changes (D, E)\\n   343→    C->>G: Stop hook (SaveChanges)\\n   344→    G->>SB: Add D, E to existing shadow branch\\n   345→    Note right of SB: Tree: B, C (from base) + D, E (new)\\n   346→    G->>S: FilesTouched = merge([B,C], [D,E]) = [B,C,D,E]\\n   347→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   348→\\n   349→    Note over U: User unstashes B, C\\n   350→    U->>U: git stash pop\\n   351→    Note right of U: B, C back in working directory\\n   352→\\n   353→    Note over U: User commits ALL files\\n   354→    U->>G: git add B C D E && git commit\\n   355→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg\\n   356→    G->>G: staged [B,C,D,E] ∩ FilesTouched [B,C,D,E] → all match ✓\\n   357→    G->>G: checkpoint-2 trailer added\\n   358→\\n   359→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   360→    G->>G: committedFiles = {B, C, D, E}\\n   361→    G->>G: remaining = []\\n   362→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   363→    Note right of G: Checkpoint includes ALL files (B,C,D,E)<br/>and FULL transcript (both prompts)\\n   364→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   365→```\\n   366→\\n   367→### Key Points\\n   368→- **Shadow branch accumulates**: D, E added on top of existing B, C from carry-forward\\n   369→- **All files tracked**: When user commits all together, all four files link to checkpoint\\n   370→- **Full session context**: Checkpoint transcript shows Prompt 1 created B, C and Prompt 2 created D, E\\n   371→\\n   372→### Contrast with Scenario 5\\n   373→\\n   374→| Scenario | User Action | Result |\\n   375→|----------|-------------|--------|\\n   376→| **5**: Commit D, E first, then B, C later | Commits D, E while B, C stashed | B, C \\\"fall out\\\" - carry-forward fails, later commit of B, C has no shadow content |\\n   377→| **6**: Commit all together after unstash | Unstashes B, C, commits B, C, D, E together | All files linked to single checkpoint |\\n   378→\\n   379→The key difference is **when the commit happens relative to the unstash**:\\n   380→- If you commit while files are stashed → those files lose their shadow branch content\\n   381→- If you unstash first, then commit → all files are preserved together\\n   382→\\n   383→---\\n   384→\\n   385→## Scenario 7: Partial Staging with `git add -p`\\n   386→\\n   387→User uses interactive staging to commit only some hunks of a file, leaving other agent changes uncommitted.\\n   388→\\n   389→```mermaid\\n   390→sequenceDiagram\\n   391→    participant U as User\\n   392→    participant C as Claude\\n   393→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   394→    participant S as Session State\\n   395→    participant SB as Shadow Branch\\n   396→\\n   397→    U->>C: Submit prompt\\n   398→    Note over G: UserPromptSubmit → ACTIVE\\n   399→\\n   400→    C->>C: Makes multiple changes to file A\\n   401→    Note right of C: A now has lines 1-100<br/>(was empty before)\\n   402→    C->>G: Stop hook\\n   403→    G->>SB: Checkpoint (A with lines 1-100)\\n   404→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A]\\n   405→    Note over G: ACTIVE→IDLE\\n   406→\\n   407→    Note over U: User stages partial content\\n   408→    U->>G: git add -p A\\n   409→    Note right of U: Stages only lines 1-50<br/>Worktree still has 1-100\\n   410→\\n   411→    U->>G: git commit\\n   412→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-1\\n   413→\\n   414→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   415→    G->>G: committedFiles = {A}\\n   416→    G->>G: Content check: committed A (lines 1-50)\\n   417→    G->>G: Shadow A hash ≠ committed A hash\\n   418→    G->>G: remaining = [A] (has uncommitted changes)\\n   419→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-1\\n   420→    G->>SB: Carry-forward A to new shadow branch\\n   421→    Note right of SB: New shadow has A with<br/>current worktree (lines 1-100)\\n   422→    G->>S: FilesTouched = [A]\\n   423→\\n   424→    Note over U: User commits remaining\\n   425→    U->>G: git add A && git commit\\n   426→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg: checkpoint-2\\n   427→\\n   428→    Note over G: PostCommit\\n   429→    G->>G: Content check: committed A == shadow A\\n   430→    G->>G: remaining = []\\n   431→    G->>SB: Condense checkpoint-2\\n   432→    G->>S: FilesTouched = nil\\n   433→```\\n   434→\\n   435→### Key Points\\n   436→- **Content-aware carry-forward**: Compares git blob hashes, not just filenames\\n   437→- Partial staging (`git add -p`) within a single file is detected\\n   438→- Each commit gets proper attribution, even when splitting one file's changes\\n   439→\\n   440→### How Content Comparison Works\\n   441→\\n   442→```mermaid\\n   443→flowchart TD\\n   444→    A[PostCommit: Carry-forward check] --> B{File in committedFiles?}\\n   445→    B -->|No| C[✓ Add to remaining<br/>File not committed at all]\\n   446→    B -->|Yes| D[Get shadow branch file hash]\\n   447→    D --> E{Shadow file exists?}\\n   448→    E -->|No| F[Skip file<br/>Nothing to compare against]\\n   449→    E -->|Yes| G{Committed hash == shadow hash?}\\n   450→    G -->|Yes| H[Skip file<br/>Fully committed]\\n   451→    G -->|No| I[✓ Add to remaining<br/>Partial commit detected]\\n   452→\\n   453→    C --> J[Carry forward remaining files]\\n   454→    I --> J\\n   455→```\\n   456→\\n   457→---\\n   458→\\n   459→## Content-Aware Overlap Detection\\n   460→\\n   461→Prevents linking commits where user reverted session changes and wrote different content.\\n   462→\\n   463→```mermaid\\n   464→flowchart TD\\n   465→    A[PostCommit: Check files overlap] --> B{File in commit AND in FilesTouched?}\\n   466→    B -->|No| Z[No checkpoint trailer]\\n   467→    B -->|Yes| C{File existed in parent commit?}\\n   468→    C -->|Yes: Modified file| D[✓ Counts as overlap<br/>User edited session's work]\\n   469→    C -->|No: New file| E{Content hash matches shadow branch?}\\n   470→    E -->|Yes| F[✓ Counts as overlap<br/>Session's content preserved]\\n   471→    E -->|No| G[✗ No overlap<br/>User reverted & replaced]\\n   472→\\n   473→    D --> H[Add checkpoint trailer]\\n   474→    F --> H\\n   475→    G --> Z\\n   476→```\\n   477→\\n   478→### Example: Reverted and Replaced\\n   479→\\n   480→```mermaid\\n   481→sequenceDiagram\\n   482→    participant U as User\\n   483→    participant C as Claude\\n   484→    participant G as Git Hooks\\n   485→\\n   486→    C->>C: Creates file X with content \\\"hello\\\"\\n   487→    Note over G: Shadow branch: X (hash: abc123)\\n   488→\\n   489→    U->>U: Reverts: git checkout -- X\\n   490→    U->>U: Writes completely different content\\n   491→    Note right of U: X now has content \\\"world\\\"<br/>(hash: def456)\\n   492→\\n   493→    U->>G: git add X && git commit\\n   494→    Note over G: PrepareCommitMsg\\n   495→    G->>G: X in FilesTouched? Yes\\n   496→    G->>G: X is new file (not in parent)\\n   497→    G->>G: Compare hashes: abc123 ≠ def456\\n   498→    G->>G: Content mismatch → NO overlap\\n   499→    Note over G: No Entire-Checkpoint trailer added\\n   500→```\\n   501→\\n   502→---\\n   503→\\n   504→## Summary Table\\n   505→\\n   506→| Scenario | When Checkpoint Created | Checkpoint Contains | Key Mechanism |\\n   507→|----------|------------------------|---------------------|---------------|\\n   508→| 1. User commits after prompt | PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript | Normal condensation |\\n   509→| 2. Claude commits in turn | PostCommit (ACTIVE) + HandleTurnEnd | Full transcript (finalized at stop) | Deferred finalization |\\n   510→| 3. Multiple Claude commits | Each PostCommit (ACTIVE) + HandleTurnEnd | Full transcript per checkpoint | TurnCheckpointIDs tracking |\\n   511→| 4. User splits commits | Each PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript per checkpoint | Content-aware carry-forward |\\n   512→| 5. Partial commit + stash + new prompt + commit new | PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript (both prompts) | FilesTouched accumulation, stashed files \\\"fall out\\\" |\\n   513→| 6. Stash + new prompt + unstash + commit all | PostCommit (IDLE) | All files + full transcript | Shadow branch accumulation |\\n   514→| 7. Partial staging with `git add -p` | Each PostCommit (IDLE) | Full transcript per checkpoint | Content-aware carry-forward (hash comparison) |\\n   515→\\n   516→---\\n   517→\\n   518→## Known Caveats\\n   519→\\n   520→### 1. Redundant Transcript Data Across Commits\\n   521→\\n   522→Each checkpoint stores the **full session transcript** up to that point. If a session results in multiple commits (Scenarios 3, 4, 5, 6), each checkpoint contains overlapping transcript data.\\n   523→\\n   524→**Example**: Session with 3 commits\\n   525→- Checkpoint 1: transcript lines 1-100\\n   526→- Checkpoint 2: transcript lines 1-200 (includes 1-100 again)\\n   527→- Checkpoint 3: transcript lines 1-300 (includes 1-200 again)\\n   528→\\n   529→**Trade-off**: This simplifies checkpoint retrieval (each is self-contained) at the cost of storage efficiency.\\n   530→\\n   531→### 2. Token Usage Sums Are Misleading\\n   532→\\n   533→Each checkpoint's `metadata.json` contains cumulative token usage for the entire session up to that point. Summing token counts across multiple checkpoints from the same session **double-counts tokens**.\\n   534→\\n   535→**Example**:\\n   536→- Checkpoint 1: 10,000 tokens (session total so far)\\n   537→- Checkpoint 2: 25,000 tokens (session total so far)\\n   538→- Naive sum: 35,000 tokens ❌\\n   539→- Actual usage: 25,000 tokens ✓\\n   540→\\n   541→**Correct approach**: Use the token count from the **last checkpoint** of a session, or track incremental deltas separately.\\n   542→\\n   543→### 3. Stashed Files Lose Shadow Content\\n   544→\\n   545→As described in Scenario 5, if files are stashed and other files are committed first, the stashed files lose their content in the shadow branch. They remain tracked by filename in `FilesTouched`, but subsequent checkpoints won't have the original file content preserved.\\n   546→\\n   547→### 4. No Per-File Prompt Attribution\\n   548→\\n   549→Checkpoints don't explicitly tag which prompt created which file. To determine this, you must parse the transcript and correlate `tool_use` entries with preceding `user` messages. The `files_touched` list in metadata is cumulative across all prompts.\\n   550→\\n   551→### 5. Carry-Forward Checkpoints Include Full Transcript\\n   552→\\n   553→When files are carried forward (Scenario 4), `CheckpointTranscriptStart` is reset to 0. This means each carry-forward checkpoint includes the **entire transcript**, not just new content since the last checkpoint.\\n   554→\\n   555→**Impact**: For long sessions with many partial commits, checkpoint storage grows linearly with session length × number of commits.\\n   556→\\n   557→### 6. Crash Before HandleTurnEnd Leaves Provisional Transcripts\\n   558→\\n   559→In Scenarios 2 and 3 (Claude commits during turn), checkpoints are saved with \\\"provisional\\\" transcripts during PostCommit. The full transcript is written at HandleTurnEnd (Stop hook).\\n   560→\\n   561→If the session crashes or is killed before the Stop hook fires:\\n   562→- Checkpoints exist with partial transcripts\\n   563→- `TurnCheckpointIDs` in session state tracks which need finalization\\n   564→- Next session start does **not** automatically finalize orphaned checkpoints\\n   565→\\n   566→### 7. Two Different Content-Aware Checks\\n   567→\\n   568→The system uses two separate content-aware checks with different purposes:\\n   569→\\n   570→**A. Overlap Detection** (`filesOverlapWithContent`) - Determines if commit should be linked to session:\\n   571→- Only applies to **newly created files**\\n   572→- Modified files (existed in parent) **always count as overlap**\\n   573→- Used in PrepareCommitMsg/PostCommit for non-ACTIVE sessions\\n   574→- **Purpose**: Prevent linking commits where user reverted session content\\n   575→\\n   576→**B. Carry-Forward Detection** (`filesWithRemainingAgentChanges`) - Determines which files to carry forward:\\n   577→- Applies to **all committed files**\\n   578→- Compares committed content hash vs shadow branch hash\\n   579→- Hash mismatch = partial commit, file carried forward\\n   580→- **Purpose**: Enable splitting changes within a file across commits (Scenario 7)\\n   581→\\n   582→### 8. Carry-Forward Content Superseded by New Prompts\\n   583→\\n   584→When files are carried forward and then a new prompt modifies the same file:\\n   585→- The shadow branch gets the **new** content (from the new prompt's SaveChanges)\\n   586→- The carried-forward content is overwritten\\n   587→- Subsequent commits compare against the **new prompt's content**, not the original carried-forward content\\n   588→\\n   589→**Example**:\\n   590→1. Prompt 1: Agent writes 100 lines to file A\\n   591→2. User commits 50 lines via `git add -p`\\n   592→3. Carry-forward: A (with 100 lines) goes to new shadow branch\\n   593→4. Prompt 2: Agent adds 50 more lines to A (now 150 lines total in worktree)\\n   594→5. SaveChanges: Shadow branch now has A with 150 lines\\n   595→6. User commits: Comparison is against 150 lines, not original 100 lines\\n   596→\\n   597→This is correct behavior - the shadow branch reflects the **current combined state** of the session's work.\\n   598→\\n   599→### 9. Automatic Cleanup During Normal Operations\\n   600→\\n   601→Most orphaned data is cleaned up automatically:\\n   602→\\n   603→- **Shadow branches**: Deleted after condensation if no other sessions reference them\\n   604→- **Session states**: Cleaned up during session listing when shadow branch no longer exists (and session is not ACTIVE, has no `LastCheckpointID`)\\n   605→\\n   606→For anything that slips through, run `entire clean` manually:\\n   607→\\n   608→```bash\\n   609→entire clean          # Preview orphaned items\\n   610→entire clean --force  # Delete orphaned items\\n   611→```\\n   612→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"124582fe-b6fd-458a-84f7-4507c65255bb\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:32:27.617Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"I need to find all E2E test function names in the e2e/tests/ directory and understand the test progression/tiers. Search for all `func Test` declarations in e2e/tests/ and also check e2e/README.md for any tier documentation. Return the full list of test function names and any tier/ordering information.\",\"agentId\":\"aa307aecb480efc9b\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01QtpEfJnyAV6sznan3xQTiZ\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01W7Ez4ig9AR7DQDJGuyjBjC\",\"uuid\":\"71ca7eda-698b-425d-b0b9-45cc76458cdd\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-26T23:32:27.618Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"71ca7eda-698b-425d-b0b9-45cc76458cdd\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"b6cafcb4-1